<meta name="socialpost1" content="Critics claim large solar farms are a public health threat. Despite little reputable evidence for this, their fears have helped undercut efforts across the U.S. to broaden energy sources, slowing installations even as customer costs are rising." />
<meta name="socialpost2" content="There’s no scientific basis to many of the public health concerns some critics have with solar development, an expert told ProPublica. “People try to come up with a rationale to justify their dislike of things they dislike for other reasons.”" />
<meta name="socialpost3" content="A Michigan county’s medical director argued that solar farms were a health hazard. Local officials then adopted new limits on solar development — even though the director’s memos didn’t offer any detailed proof of his claims." />
<meta name="socialpost4" content="New solar installations in the U.S. dropped by 14% last year. Among the challenges: pushback from critics who claim, without evidence, that solar panels pose a health threat." />
<meta name="socialpost5" content="Despite its goal of 100% clean energy by 2040, Michigan has more local restrictions on renewable energy than any other state. “Practically nowhere in the country has seen more conflict” about solar development, a research center found." />
